<paragraph id="8B8BD24E356388227F9DFA07FEA76CBF" blockId="21.[151,1436,1483,1652]" box="[151,263,1483,1508]" pageId="21" pageNumber="344">Diagnosis</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8BD24E356388227F9DFA22FB706F2F" blockId="21.[151,1436,1483,1652]" pageId="21" pageNumber="344">
Morphologically this species could not be confused to any other, thanks to its pronotal reddish blunt tubercles, to the absence of the terminal spine of the posterior process (in common only with 
<taxonomicName id="4C34A9CD356388227B17F9D8FB2A6F70" box="[1053,1162,1555,1579]" class="Insecta" family="Membracidae" genus="Hamma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="344" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="carlini">
<emphasis id="B9400E5C356388227B17F9D8FB2A6F70" box="[1053,1162,1555,1579]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="344">H. carlini</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), and to the compressed from above view but laterally large first node of the posterior process. Superficially, its posterior process looks like the one of 
<taxonomicName id="4C34A9CD356388227E04F990FE0E6F28" box="[270,430,1627,1651]" class="Insecta" family="Membracidae" genus="Hamma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="344" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ugandensis">
<emphasis id="B9400E5C356388227E04F990FE0E6F28" box="[270,430,1627,1651]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="344">H. ugandensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in lateral view, but every other view and character are clearly different.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8BD24E356388227F9DF96FFF686FE7" blockId="21.[151,434,1699,1831]" box="[151,200,1699,1724]" pageId="21" pageNumber="344">Size</paragraph>
